The s-s-h config file.

Typing out a long s-s-h command, with a specific key, a custom port, a username, and a lengthy hostname, gets tiresome very fast. The s-s-h configuration file, kept in your s-s-h directory, lets you save all of that behind a simple alias.

The file is organised into host blocks. Each block begins with the word host and an alias of your choosing, and inside it you set the real details. The host-name property gives the actual hostname or address, the user property gives the username, port gives a custom port, and identity-file names the private key to use. So you might define a block called work that points at a particular internal address, logs in as a particular user, and uses a particular key. From then on you simply type s-s-h work, and all those settings are applied for you.

A few rules govern how the file is read. Each host block applies to hostnames that match it, and for any given option the first match wins, so order matters. A block written as host, then a star, placed at the end, sets defaults for every connection, and the patterns can use glob-style wildcards to match a whole family of hosts. Beyond the basic four properties, two are especially worth knowing. Proxy-jump tells s-s-h to route the connection through an intermediate host first, which is exactly how you reach machines behind a bastion. And server-alive-interval sends periodic keepalives so that idle connections are not silently dropped by network equipment in between. For the exam, be comfortable with the basic pattern of host, host-name, user, and identity-file.
